<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Select the top 50 listings by number of reviews per month</span>
<span class="n">top_50</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">nlargest</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">50</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'reviews per month'</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Sort the data by number of reviews per month in descending order</span>
<span class="n">top_50</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">top_50</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sort_values</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'reviews per month'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ascending</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Define the color map to use</span>
<span class="n">cmap</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">get_cmap</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'GnBu'</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Create the bar chart</span>
<span class="n">fig</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">bars</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">bar</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">top_50</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'NAME'</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">top_50</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'reviews per month'</span><span class="p">])</span>

<span class="c1"># Set the color of each bar based on its value</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">bars</span><span class="p">)):</span>
    <span class="n">bars</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_color</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">cmap</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="n">bars</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">get_height</span><span class="p">()</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">min</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">top_50</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'reviews per month'</span><span class="p">]))</span> 
                           <span class="o">/</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">max</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">top_50</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'reviews per month'</span><span class="p">])</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">min</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">top_50</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'reviews per month'</span><span class="p">]))))</span>

<span class="c1"># Set the chart title and axis labels</span>

<p>Our analysis shows that, on average, Staten Island has the highest number of available listings despite having the lowest total number of listings. Meanwhile, Brooklyn typically has the lowest number of available listings despite having the second-highest total number of listings. The majority of the rooms available are private or entire home/apartment. Staten Island typically has a higher average review rate, while Brooklyn and Manhattan have lower average review rates. Prices do not appear to vary with room type, and price should be a good indicator of service fees. The "word map" shows that "smoking," "pet," "rules," "don't," and "respectful/respect" are the most frequently mentioned words in the rules made by hosts.</p>
